On 10 April 2010 President Kaczyński was killed, with 96 others, including the President of the National Bank of Poland and the Chief of Staff of the Defence Forces, in an air crash in the Russian Federation. In accordance with the Constitution, Marshal of the Assembly Bronisław Komorowski was appointed acting President and a presidential election was scheduled. In May some 2,500 people demonstrated outside the presidential palace in Warsaw to demand an independent inquiry into the crash (see 
Regional Relations
).

In early February 2022 Kościński resigned as Minister of Finance, following criticism of the Government’s implementation of a controversial package of tax reforms, which took effect at the beginning of the year. Following Russia’s invasion of Ukraine (see 
Regional Relations
), in mid-March the Assembly approved legislation on the provision of assistance to Ukrainian refugees arriving in Poland (who rapidly numbered some 1.5m.), granting them the legal right to remain in the country for a period of up to three years and to obtain social benefits. All remaining restrictions imposed in response to the COVID-19 pandemic in Poland were lifted on 28 March.

Magdalena Rzeczkowska, an independent and hitherto head of the National Revenue Administration, was appointed to succeed Kościński as Minister of Finance in April 2022. On 20 June Kaczyński announced his resignation as Deputy Prime Minister in order to focus on his role as leader of PiS prior to the next elections; he was succeeded by Minister of National Defence Błaszczak (who retained his previous post). A final version of legislation that had been proposed by President Duda in February, providing for the closure of the judicial disciplinary chamber of the Supreme Court and its replacement by a new Chamber of Professional Responsibility tasked with holding judges to account, was approved by the Assembly on 9 June; the Assembly rejected a number of amendments proposed by the opposition, which claimed that the new chamber would also be under government control. (The legislation was signed into law by Duda on 13 June.) The disciplinary chamber was dissolved in mid-July and the successor Chamber of Professional Responsibility, comprising 11 members selected by Duda from Supreme Court judges, subsequently established. On 13 January 2023 the Assembly approved legislation that would further reverse some of the previous contentious judicial reforms, including by transferring judicial disciplinary matters from the Supreme Court to the Supreme Administrative Court. The European Commission in April rejected a government application for the daily €1m. fine levied against Poland to be suspended; however, shortly afterwards the ECJ reduced the fine to €500,000. Meanwhile, Henryk Kowalczyk announced his resignation as Minister of Agriculture and Rural Development in early April (retaining his concurrent post as Deputy Prime Minister), following protests by farmers’ groups (see 
Regional Relations
), which accused him of mismanagement.


On 26 May 2023 the Assembly adopted a law creating a `State Commission to Investigate Russian Influence on Internal Security in the Republic of Poland’, which would investigate whether senior officials had acted to the detriment of public interest between 2007 and 2022 and, prior to parliamentary elections, would be empowered to ban any political figure from holding most public office for 10 years. The new law, which prompted accusations from opposition parties that it targeted the actions of PO administrations between 2007 and 2015, and specifically PO leader Tusk, also caused the EU and the USA to express strong concerns. Nevertheless, it was signed by President Duda on 29 May and entered into force on 31 May. Shortly afterwards, Duda announced that he had submitted several proposed revisions to the legislation for urgent parliamentary consideration. The PO organized mass protests against the law in major cities on 4 June; the rallies in Warsaw numbered up to 500,000 people (according to opposition estimates) and were attended by leading activists, including former President Wałęsa. On 8 June the European Commission opened an infringement procedure against Poland, considering that the legislation was in violation of EU law. The proposed amendments to the legislation, which notably removed the authority of the commission to ban figures from public office and allowed the right to appeal against its decisions, were adopted in early August. Meanwhile, on 21 June Kaczyński returned to the Government as its only Deputy Prime Minister, as the four incumbent deputy premiers resigned at the same time (while retaining their ministerial portfolios). On 17 August the Assembly approved a resolution to schedule a national referendum concerning economic and migration issues concurrently with the elections; four questions were to be posed to voters, on whether they supported, respectively, the sale of state assets to foreign entities, an increase in the retirement age, the removal of the barrier on Poland’s border with Belarus (see 
Regional Relations
), and the admission of large numbers of immigrants under the EU’s relocation mechanism. Opposition parties objected to the phrasing of the referendum questions, which was considered to be biased and designed to reflect PiS attacks on the opposition, and urged a boycott of the vote.

Amid renewed protests by farmers over Ukrainian agricultural imports (see 
Regional Relations
), on 27 February 2024 a mass rally was staged in Warsaw to demand the closure of the border with Ukraine and the abolition of EU environmental policies. Despite negotiating efforts by the PO Government, the farmers’ protest campaign, supported by the PiS-affiliated Solidarność union, continued during March, with tractor blockades of major roads around cities.

In mid-March 2023 Poland (with Slovakia following shortly afterwards) became the first NATO country to pledge to supply Ukraine with fighter jets, and the first Polish delivery was announced in early April. Amid protests over the impact of cheap Ukrainian grain imports on local prices (see 
Domestic Political Affairs
), Zelensky made a state visit to Warsaw on 5 April, when he and Prime Minister Morawiecki signed a letter of intent to co-operate on the supply of defence equipment to Ukraine. Later that month the Polish Government announced the construction of a 200-km barrier along the border with Russia’s Kaliningrad exclave in order to monitor and counteract any illegal activity.

Following the establishment of a PO-led Government in December 2023 (see 
Domestic Political Affairs
), Minister of Justice Adam Bodnar in February 2024 presented to the EU an action plan designed to restore the independence of the judiciary in Poland. Shortly afterwards, President of the European Commission Ursula von der Leyen and the Prime Minister of Belgium (which held the EU Presidency) visited Warsaw, when it was confirmed that the EU had decided to unblock the RRF and cohesion funds allocated to Poland. The first RRF payment of €6.300m. was accordingly released in mid-April.

In response to the annexation of Ukraine’s Crimean peninsula by Russia (see 
Regional Relations
), in April 2014 the USA stationed 150 troops in Poland to begin a series of training exercises. In September the defence ministers of Poland, Lithuania and Ukraine signed an agreement in Warsaw that provided for the creation of a joint military force, the Lithuanian-Polish-Ukrainian Brigade, which would participate in peacekeeping operations. In February 2015, amid continuing conflict in eastern Ukraine, NATO announced plans to establish an expanded rapid reaction force to counter possible Russian aggression. At a NATO summit meeting, held in Warsaw on 8 July 2016, the deployment, on a rotating basis, of four multinational battalions to Poland and the three Baltic states (Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania), respectively, was confirmed. Meanwhile, in January a ceremony to mark the creation of the 4,500-member Lithuanian-Polish-Ukrainian Brigade took place in the eastern town of Lublin. The NATO battalion was deployed in the north-eastern town of Orzysz from April.
